{"title_page": "2009 Loft Law Amendment", "text_new": "The '''Loft Law Amendment''' (also referred to as '''Expanded Loft Law''') is a [[New York law]] that created a new [[window period]] for recognition of [[loft]] [[Leasehold estate|tenants]] that previously did not qualify under the original [[1982 Loft Law]].\n\nThe purpose of this bill is to extend provisions of the Loft Law to buildings which have been occupied residentially for 12 consecutive months during the period starting January 1, 2008 and ending December 31, 2009.\n\n==Legislative history==\n\n[[United States Senator|Senator]] [[Martin Malave Dilan]] introduced the \"Expanded Loft Law\" in the [[United States Senate|Senate]] in 2010. The 2010 version of the bill is coded as S7178A.<ref>http://open.nysenate.gov/legislation/bill/S7178A</ref> The bill was amended in May 2010 and passed in the [[New York State Assembly]] (A05667C<ref>http://open.nysenate.gov/legislation/bill/A5667C</ref>) on June 3, 2010. On June 8, 2010, the [[New York State Senate]] passed the \u201cExpanded Loft Law\u201d, bill [http://www.nysenate.gov/press-release/legislation-sponsored-senator-dilan-protect-loft-tenants-permanently-passes-senate S7178A]. The bill awaits the Governor's approval.\n\n==Provisions==\n*Amends the definition of loft dwellings to include [[commercial building|commercial]] or [[manufacturing]] buildings occupied for residential purposes for 12 consecutive months from January 1, 2008 to December 31, 2009 and extends Loft Law protections to tenants in such buildings<ref>http://www.nysenate.gov/press-release/senate-majority-ensures-affordable-housing-loft-tenants</ref>\n*Requires non-residential space in such buildings to be offered for [[residential]] use only after a residential [[certificate of occupancy]] has been obtained for such space\n*Requires owners of loft buildings to achieve compliance with the standards of [[safety]] and [[fire protection]], and take reasonable and necessary action to obtain certificate of occupancy as a class A multiple dwelling for the residential portion of the building\n*Authorizes the [[New York City Loft Board|Loft Board]] to extend any [[regulatory compliance|compliance]] deadline that an owner is unable to meet for reasons beyond his or her control\n*Authorizes the Loft Board, upon good cause shown, to extend the time of compliance twice with the requirement to obtain a residential certificate of occupancy for periods not to exceed 12 months each\n*Allows owners of such buildings to apply to the Loft Board for an exemption of a building if the owner can show it would cause an unjustifiable hardship\n*Provides that these interim multiple dwellings become subject to the [[New York City Rent Stabilization Law]] after they are legalized\n*Makes the Loft Law permanent\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.assembly.state.ny.us/leg/?bn=A05667&sh=t Text of New York State Assembly Bill A05667A - also referred to as the Loft Law Amendment]\n* [http://open.nysenate.gov/legislation/bill/S7178A New York State Senate OPEN Legislation search - S7178A]\n* [http://nyclofttenants.org New York City Loft Tenants information site]\n\n[[Category:2009 in American law]]\n[[Category:2009 in New York City]]\n[[Category:Affordable housing]]\n[[Category:Real property law in the United States]]\n[[Category:Government of New York City]]\n\n\n\n{{US-law-stub}}\n", "text_old": "The '''Loft Law Amendment''' (also referred to as '''Expanded Loft Law''') is a [[New York law]] that created a new [[window period]] for recognition of [[loft]] [[Leasehold estate|tenants]] that previously did not qualify under the original [[1982 Loft Law]].\n\nThe purpose of this bill is to extend provisions of the Loft Law to buildings which have been occupied residentially for 12 consecutive months during the period starting January 1, 2008 and ending December 31, 2009.\n\n==Legislative history==\n\n[[United States Senator|Senator]] [[Martin Malave Dilan]] introduced the \"Expanded Loft Law\" in the [[United States Senate|Senate]] in 2010. The 2010 version of the bill is coded as S7178A.<ref>http://open.nysenate.gov/legislation/bill/S7178A</ref> The bill was amended in May 2010 and passed in the [[New York State Assembly]] (A05667C<ref>http://open.nysenate.gov/legislation/bill/A5667C</ref>) on June 3, 2010. On June 8, 2010, the [[New York State Senate]] passed the \u201cExpanded Loft Law\u201d, bill [http://www.nysenate.gov/press-release/legislation-sponsored-senator-dilan-protect-loft-tenants-permanently-passes-senate S7178A]. The bill awaits the Governor\u2019s approval.\n\n==Provisions==\n*Amends the definition of loft dwellings to include [[commercial building|commercial]] or [[manufacturing]] buildings occupied for residential purposes for 12 consecutive months from January 1, 2008 to December 31, 2009 and extends Loft Law protections to tenants in such buildings<ref>http://www.nysenate.gov/press-release/senate-majority-ensures-affordable-housing-loft-tenants</ref>\n*Requires non-residential space in such buildings to be offered for [[residential]] use only after a residential [[certificate of occupancy]] has been obtained for such space\n*Requires owners of loft buildings to achieve compliance with the standards of [[safety]] and [[fire protection]], and take reasonable and necessary action to obtain certificate of occupancy as a class A multiple dwelling for the residential portion of the building\n*Authorizes the [[New York City Loft Board|Loft Board]] to extend any [[regulatory compliance|compliance]] deadline that an owner is unable to meet for reasons beyond his or her control\n*Authorizes the Loft Board, upon good cause shown, to extend the time of compliance twice with the requirement to obtain a residential certificate of occupancy for periods not to exceed 12 months each\n*Allows owners of such buildings to apply to the Loft Board for an exemption of a building if the owner can show it would cause an unjustifiable hardship\n*Provides that these interim multiple dwellings become subject to the [[New York City Rent Stabilization Law]] after they are legalized\n*Makes the Loft Law permanent\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.assembly.state.ny.us/leg/?bn=A05667&sh=t Text of New York State Assembly Bill A05667A - also referred to as the Loft Law Amendment]\n* [http://open.nysenate.gov/legislation/bill/S7178A New York State Senate OPEN Legislation search - S7178A]\n* [http://nyclofttenants.org New York City Loft Tenants information site]\n\n[[Category:2009 in American law]]\n[[Category:2009 in New York City]]\n[[Category:Affordable housing]]\n[[Category:Real property law in the United States]]\n[[Category:Government of New York City]]\n\n\n\n{{US-law-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLegislative history:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2009_Loft_Law_Amendment"}
{"title_page": "Verfassungsbeschwerde", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n{{Unreferenced|date=July 2010}}\nThe '''constitutional complaint''' ('''''Verfassungsbeschwerde''''') is a remedy found in [[Germany]] for protection of [[constitutional rights]]. It derives from Article 93 Sec. 1 Nr. 4a of the [[German Basic Law|Basic Law]]. It resembles in certain respects the ''[[writ of amparo|amparo]]'' remedy available in some Spanish-speaking nations.\n\nThe constitutional complaint is an extraordinary remedy for the protection of constitutional rights. These are the basic rights (Art. 1 - 19 GG) and certain related rights (Art. 20 Sec. 4, Art. 33, Art. 38, Art. 101, Art. 103, Art. 104 GG).\n\nThe constitutional complaint originally was only part of a federal law (\u00a7\u00a7 90 ff. BVerfGG) and not part of the constitution itself. Yet it was incorporated in the Constitution in 1969, because at the same time the so-called [[:de:Notstandsverfassung|Notstandsverfassung]] (regulations for the case of emergency and war) was incorporated in the constitution. In case of emergency it is possible to impose restrictions on the citizens in respect to certain basic rights. In order to avoid the possibility of simple changes of the federal law, the remedy was incorporated in the constitution.\n\nThe constitutional complaint is not a popular action. Although everyone can take action, the appellant must meet certain requirements:\nThe appellant must allege that their above-mentioned constitutional rights have been violated by an act of German (not [[European Union|EU]]) public authorities (be it [[Executive (government)|executive]], [[judicial]] or [[legislative]]).\n\nThe appellant needs to be affected \n- himself,\n- currently, and\n- immediately.\n\nThe latter requirement will normally only be met by constitutional complaints against judgments and against acts of the executive. Laws are normally not self-executing.\nAs an extraordinary remedy the constitutional complaint is subsidiary to the regular remedies. This means two things. In the first place the appellant must have used every possible other remedy (also the remedy in case of infringement of the claim for hearing). This is why practically, constitutional complaints are mostly directed against judicial acts, not acts of the executive (which can still be contested at the [[administrative court]]). Secondly (and the reason why so many complaints are dismissed as inadmissible), the appellant must have already claimed the violation of the above-mentioned rights while making use of the regular remedies.\n\nThe complaint must be written. And it is subject to a deadline. Against laws the deadline is one year after the coming into force. For the other cases it is one month after the service / notification.\nThe appellant can be a legal person, as far as the above-mentioned rights \"fit\" (Art. 19 Sec. 3 GG).\n{{Germany-law-stub}}\n[[Category:German constitutional law]]\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n{{Unreferenced|date=July 2010}}\nThe '''constitutional complaint''' ('''''Verfassungsbeschwerde''''') is a remedy found in [[Germany]] for protection of [[constitutional rights]]. It derives from Article 93 Sec. 1 Nr. 4a of the [[German Basic Law|Basic Law]]. It resembles in certain respects the ''[[writ of amparo|amparo]]'' remedy available in some Spanish-speaking nations.\n\nThe constitutional complaint is an extraordinary remedy for the protection of constitutional rights. These are the basic rights (Art. 1 - 19 GG) and certain related rights (Art. 20 Sec. 4, Art. 33, Art. 38, Art. 101, Art. 103, Art. 104 GG).\n\nThe constitutional complaint originally was only part of a federal law (\u00a7\u00a7 90 ff. BVerfGG) and not part of the constitution itself. Yet it was incorporated in the Constitution in 1969, because at the same time the so-called [[:de:Notstandsverfassung|Notstandsverfassung]] (regulations for the case of emergency and war) was incorporated in the constitution. In case of emergency it is possible to impose restrictions on the citizens in respect to certain basic rights. In order to avoid the possibility of simple changes of the federal law, the remedy was incorporated in the constitution.\n\nThe constitutional complaint is not a popular action. Although everyone can take action, the appellant must meet certain requirements:\nThe appellant must allege that their above-mentioned constitutional rights have been violated by an act of German (not [[European Union|EU]]) public authorities (be it [[Executive (government)|executive]], [[judicial]] or [[legislative]]).\n\nThe appellant needs to be affected \n- himself,\n- currently, and\n- immediately.\n\nThe latter requirement will normally only be met by constitutional complaints against judgments and against acts of the executive. Laws are normally not self-executing.\nAs an extraordinary remedy the constitutional complaint is subsidiary to the regular remedies. This means two things. In the first place the appellant must have used every possible other remedy (also the remedy in case of infringement of the claim for hearing). This is why practically, constitutional complaints are mostly directed against judicial acts, not acts of the executive (which can still be contested at the [[administrative court]]). Secondly (and the reason why so many complaints are dismissed as inadmissible), the appellant must have already claimed the violation of the above-mentioned rights while making use of the regular remedies.\n\nThe complaint must be written. And it is subject to a deadline. Against laws the deadline is one year after the coming into force. For the other cases it is one month after the service / notification.\nThe appellant can be a legal person, as far as the above mentioned rights \"fit\" (Art. 19 Sec. 3 GG).\n{{Germany-law-stub}}\n[[Category:German constitutional law]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: above mentioned \u2192 above-mentioned", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Verfassungsbeschwerde"}
{"title_page": "North Creek School", "text_new": "{{Cleanup bare URLs |bot=wp:tagbot |requester=User:Mdaniels5757 |date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox NRHP\n| name = North Creek School\n| nrhp_type = \n| image = North Creek School 2012-09-30 22-07-13.jpg\n| caption = \n| location = 1129 208th Street SE,<br/>[[Bothell, Washington]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|47.80873|-122.21725|region:US-WA_type:edu|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = Washington#USA\n| built = {{Start date|1902}}\n| architect = \n| architecture = One-room schoolhouse\n| added = May 19, 1994\n| area = less than one acre\n| refnum = 94000406<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''North Creek School''' is a school building located in [[Bothell, Washington]] listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nps.gov/nr/research/ |title=National Register of Historic Places Program: Research |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140115150111/http://www.nps.gov/nr/research/ |archive-date=2014-01-15 |access-date=2014-02-06}}</ref>  Built in 1902, it served as a school for 18 years. The first teacher was Edgar Turner, who homesteaded at the present Turner's Corner (Highway 9 and Maltby Road intersection).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.snocohistory.com/life-along-the-highway/turners_corner_woodinville |title=Turner\u2019s Corner, Woodinville - Historic Corners - Past:Forward |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150218023930/http://www.snocohistory.com/life-along-the-highway/turners_corner_woodinville |archive-date=2015-02-18 |access-date=2015-02-17}}</ref>  Another of the school's teachers was Charles V. Beardslee, who came to the Bothell area in the late 1880s.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tdB2ApOwEKo |title=Historic North Creek School House, Bothell WA |website=YouTube |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426191132/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tdB2ApOwEKo |archive-date=2016-04-26 |access-date=2016-12-01}}</ref> After closing in 1920, it served as a meeting location for the Canyon Park Community Club until about 1950.  It was then used for storage for many years, deteriorating from lack of use and nonattendance.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://seattletimes.com/html/eastsidenews/2003029768_oldschool31e.html |title=The Seattle Times &#124; Local news, sports, business, politics, entertainment, travel, restaurants and opinion for Seattle and the Pacific Northwest |access-date=2015-02-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150218024149/http://seattletimes.com/html/eastsidenews/2003029768_oldschool31e.html |archive-date=2015-02-18 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOriginally located on the northwest corner of 31st Avenue S.E. and 228th Street S.E., about one mile east of Canyon Park Shopping Center, in 2008 the schoolhouse was moved to Centennial Park at 1129 208th Street SE.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nwnews.com/index.php/local/news-features/9325-historic-north-creek-school-house-ribbon-cutting-ceremony-to-be-held-april-5 |title=Historic North Creek School House Ribbon-Cutting Ceremony to Be Held April 5 |last1=Michael |first1=Shannon |date=24 Mar 2014 |website=The Woodinville Weekly |publisher= |accessdate=June 8, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150126032646/http://www.nwnews.com/index.php/local/news-features/9325-historic-north-creek-school-house-ribbon-cutting-ceremony-to-be-held-april-5 |archive-date=26 January 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Snohomish County, Washington]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1902 establishments in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:School buildings completed in 1902]]\n[[Category:School buildings on the National Register of Historic Places in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Snohomish County, Washington]]\n\n\n{{Washington-NRHP-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Cleanup bare URLs |bot=wp:tagbot |requester=User:Mdaniels5757 |date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox NRHP\n| name = North Creek School\n| nrhp_type = \n| image = North Creek School 2012-09-30 22-07-13.jpg\n| caption = \n| location = 1129 208th Street SE,<br/>[[Bothell, Washington]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|47.80873|-122.21725|region:US-WA_type:edu|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = Washington#USA\n| built = {{Start date|1902}}\n| architect = \n| architecture = One-room schoolhouse\n| added = May 19, 1994\n| area = less than one acre\n| refnum = 94000406<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''North Creek School''' is a school building located in [[Bothell, Washington]] listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nps.gov/nr/research/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2014-02-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140115150111/http://www.nps.gov/nr/research/ |archive-date=2014-01-15 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Built in 1902, it served as a school for 18 years. The first teacher was Edgar Turner, who homesteaded at the present Turner's Corner (Highway 9 and Maltby Road intersection).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.snocohistory.com/life-along-the-highway/turners_corner_woodinville |title=Archived copy |access-date=2015-02-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150218023930/http://www.snocohistory.com/life-along-the-highway/turners_corner_woodinville |archive-date=2015-02-18 |url-status=live }}</ref>  Another of the school's teachers was Charles V. Beardslee, who came to the Bothell area in the late 1880s.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tdB2ApOwEKo |title=Archived copy |access-date=2016-12-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426191132/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tdB2ApOwEKo |archive-date=2016-04-26 |url-status=live }}</ref> After closing in 1920, it served as a meeting location for the Canyon Park Community Club until about 1950.  It was then used for storage for many years, deteriorating from lack of use and nonattendance.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://seattletimes.com/html/eastsidenews/2003029768_oldschool31e.html |title=The Seattle Times &#124; Local news, sports, business, politics, entertainment, travel, restaurants and opinion for Seattle and the Pacific Northwest |access-date=2015-02-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150218024149/http://seattletimes.com/html/eastsidenews/2003029768_oldschool31e.html |archive-date=2015-02-18 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOriginally located on the northwest corner of 31st Avenue S.E. and 228th Street S.E., about one mile east of Canyon Park Shopping Center, in 2008 the schoolhouse was moved to Centennial Park at 1129 208th Street SE.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nwnews.com/index.php/local/news-features/9325-historic-north-creek-school-house-ribbon-cutting-ceremony-to-be-held-april-5 |title=Historic North Creek School House Ribbon-Cutting Ceremony to Be Held April 5 |last1=Michael |first1=Shannon |date=24 Mar 2014 |website=The Woodinville Weekly |publisher= |accessdate=June 8, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150126032646/http://www.nwnews.com/index.php/local/news-features/9325-historic-north-creek-school-house-ribbon-cutting-ceremony-to-be-held-april-5 |archive-date=26 January 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Snohomish County, Washington]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1902 establishments in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:School buildings completed in 1902]]\n[[Category:School buildings on the National Register of Historic Places in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Snohomish County, Washington]]\n\n\n{{Washington-NRHP-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Mdaniels5757", "label": "safe", "comment": "Update ref titles", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/North_Creek_School"}
{"title_page": "Ricardo Domeneck", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n[[File:Ricardo Domeneck at Fokus Lyrik 2019 01.jpg|thumb|Ricardo Domeneck at Fokus Lyrik 2019]]\n'''Ricardo Domeneck''' is a contemporary Brazilian [[poet]], [[visual artist]] and [[critic]], born in [[Bebedouro]] on July 4, 1977. Currently, the poet lives and works in Berlin, Germany.\n\n== Writing ==\n\nRicardo Domeneck has published four [[books]] of poetry and two [[chapbooks]] to date. His first collection of poems, entitled  ''Carta aos anf\u00edbios'' (Letter to amphibians), was published in [[Rio de Janeiro]] in 2005, released by a small [[publishing]] house. His second book, ''a cadela sem Logos'' (the bitch without Logos),  followed in 2007, this time with a major Brazilian publisher, Cosac Naify, which would also release in 2009 his third collection, ''Sons: Arranjo: Garganta'' (Sounds: Composition: Throat). His last book is titled ''Cigarros na cama'' (Cigarettes in bed), published in 2011. In English, his poems have been included in anthologies of contemporary Brazilian poetry and he has also collaborated with poetry magazines such as ''Green Integer Review'', edited by contemporary American poet Douglas Messerli. His texts have been translated into Spanish, [[Catalan language|Catalan]], French, German, [[Slovenian language|Slovenian]] and Arabic. Ricardo Domeneck is one of the editors of the online magazines Hilda and [http://www.revistamododeusar.blogspot.com Modo de Usar & Co.], and has conducted video interviews for other online magazines with artists and musicians such as [[Bat for Lashes]], [[Ellen Allien]], [[Heinz Peter Knes]] and [[Walter Pfeiffer]], among others.\n\n== Video and performance ==\n\nIn 2006, invited by the Brazilian television network known as [[TV Cultura]], Ricardo Domeneck produced his first two videos. Since then, his work has ranged from writing to the vocal performance of texts merged with [[video]]. In Berlin, Ricardo Domeneck would begin a research of the poetics of performance and sound poetry of the [[Dada]] movement, also translating poets [[Hans Arp]] and [[Pierre Albert-Birot]] and poet-[[performers]] from the Wiener Gruppe ([[H. C. Artmann]], Konrad Bayer, [[Gerhard R\u00fchm]], etc.) into Portuguese. The same year he produced his first video, Domeneck started performing in experimental poetry festivals of cities such as [[Buenos Aires]], [[Madrid]], [[Barcelona]] and [[Brussels]], including performances museums such as the Espai d\u00b4Art Contemporani in Castell\u00f3  and the Museo Reina Sof\u00eda in Madrid. The poet is also the co-founder of a collective of artists based in Berlin, which organizes weekly performances and live acts at the club Neue Berliner Initiative, including artists, musicians and bands such as [[Kevin Blechdom]], [[Wolfgang M\u00fcller (musician)|Wolfgang M\u00fcller]] of [[Die T\u00f6dliche Doris]], [[JD Samson]] and [[Johanna Fateman]] of [[Le Tigre]], [[Mystery Jets]], [[Stereo Total]], [[Mount Sims]], Shunda K of [[Yo Majesty]], [[Bruce LaBruce]] and [[Angie Reed]], among others. The collective is also responsible for the [[independent record label|independent]] [[label]] [http://www.myspace.com/kutebashrecords Kute Bash Records], which has released the London-based [[multimedia]] duo [[Tetine]]. In [[video art]], his interventions have been shown from [[nightclubs]] and [[Art museum|galleries]] in Europe to the public television in Brazil. In both his writing and videos, Ricardo Domeneck concentrates on his own body as fixed set of materials.\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n'''Poetry'''\n\n*  ''Carta aos anfibios'' (Rio de Janeiro: Editora Bem-Te-Vi, 2005) {{ISBN|85-88747-17-0}}\n*  ''a cadela sem Logos'' (S\u00e3o Paulo: Cosac Naify, 2007) {{ISBN|978-85-7503-568-9}}\n*  ''Sons: Arranjo: Garganta'' (S\u00e3o Paulo: Cosac Naify, 2009) {{ISBN|978-85-7503-778-2}}\n* ''Cigarros na cama'' (Rio de Janeiro: Berinjela/Modo de Usar & Co., 2011)\n\n'''Chapbooks'''\n\n* ''When they spoke I / confused cortex / for context'' (London: Kute Bash Books, 2006)\n* ''Corpos e palanques'' (S\u00e3o Paulo: Dulcineia Catadora, 2009)\n\n'''Anthologies in Translation'''\n\n* ''Cuatro Poetas Recientes del Brasil'' (Buenos Aires: Black & Vermelho, 2006) {{ISBN|987-22223-2-0}}\n* ''\u00dcberland und Leuchtende St\u00e4dte \u2013 12 Dichterinnen und Dichter aus Lateinamerika'' (Berlin: SuKulTur, 2006) {{ISBN|3-937737-74-X}}\n* ''Tigertail Poetry Annual: Brazil Issue'' (Miami: Tigertail, 2008).\n* ''Dnevi poezije in vina'' (Ljubljana: \u0160tudentska zalo\u017eba, 2009)\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.greeninteger.com/green_integer_review/issue_9/Ricardo-Domeneck.cfm Poems on ''Green Integer Review'' issue 9]\n* [http://www2.tvcultura.com.br/entrelinhas/videos.asp?videodata=20/12/2006 Videos on Brazilian television network TV Cultura]\n* [http://www.myspace.com/ricardodomeneck Videos and sound poems on Myspace]\n* [http://www.lateinamerikanachrichten.de/?/artikel/1007.html German article on ''Lateinamerikanachrichten'']\n* [http://p.php.uol.com.br/tropico/html/textos/2616,1.shl Portuguese article about the poet on ''Tr\u00f3pico'']\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Domeneck}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Bebedouro]]\n[[Category:21st-century Brazilian poets]]\n[[Category:Brazilian male poets]]\n[[Category:Video artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Brazilian male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n[[File:Ricardo Domeneck at Fokus Lyrik 2019 01.jpg|thumb|Ricardo Domeneck at Fokus Lyrik 2019]]\n'''Ricardo Domeneck''' is a contemporary Brazilian [[poet]], [[visual artist]] and [[critic]], born in [[Bebedouro]] on July 4, 1977. Currently, the poet lives and works in Berlin, Germany.\n\n== Writing ==\n\nRicardo Domeneck has published four [[books]] of poetry and two [[chapbooks]] to date. His first collection of poems, entitled  ''Carta aos anf\u00edbios'' (Letter to amphibians), was published in [[Rio de Janeiro]] in 2005, released by a small [[publishing]] house. His second book, ''a cadela sem Logos'' (the bitch without Logos),  followed in 2007, this time with a major Brazilian publisher, Cosac Naify, which would also release in 2009 his third collection, ''Sons: Arranjo: Garganta'' (Sounds: Composition: Throat). His last book is titled ''Cigarros na cama'' (Cigarettes in bed), published in 2011. In English, his poems have been included in anthologies of contemporary Brazilian poetry and he has also collaborated with poetry magazines such as ''Green Integer Review'', edited by contemporary American poet Douglas Messerli. His texts have been translated into Spanish, [[Catalan language|Catalan]], French, German, [[Slovenian language|Slovenian]] and Arabic. Ricardo Domeneck is one of the editors of the online magazines Hilda and [http://www.revistamododeusar.blogspot.com Modo de Usar & Co.], and has conducted video interviews for other online magazines with artists and musicians such as [[Bat for Lashes]], [[Ellen Allien]], [[Heinz Peter Knes]] and [[Walter Pfeiffer]], among others.\n\n== Video and performance ==\n\nIn 2006, invited by the Brazilian television network known as [[TV Cultura]], Ricardo Domeneck produced his first two videos. Since then, his work has ranged from writing to the vocal performance of texts merged with [[video]]. In Berlin, Ricardo Domeneck would begin a research of the poetics of performance and sound poetry of the [[Dada]] movement, also translating poets [[Hans Arp]] and [[Pierre Albert-Birot]] and poet-[[performers]] from the Wiener Gruppe ([[H. C. Artmann]], Konrad Bayer, [[Gerhard R\u00fchm]], etc.) into Portuguese. The same year he produced his first video, Domeneck started performing in experimental poetry festivals of cities such as [[Buenos Aires]], [[Madrid]], [[Barcelona]] and [[Brussels]], including performances museums such as the Espai d\u00b4Art Contemporani in Castell\u00f3  and the Museo Reina Sof\u00eda in Madrid. The poet is also the co-founder of a collective of artists based in Berlin, which organizes weekly performances and live acts at the club Neue Berliner Initiative, including artists, musicians and bands such as [[Kevin Blechdom]], [[Wolfgang M\u00fcller (musician)|Wolfgang M\u00fcller]] of [[Die T\u00f6dliche Doris]], [[JD Samson]] and [[Johanna Fateman]] of [[Le Tigre]], [[Mystery Jets]], [[Stereo Total]], [[Mount Sims]], Shunda K of [[Yo Majesty]], [[Bruce LaBruce]] and [[Angie Reed]], among others. The collective is also responsible for the [[independent record label|independent]] [[label]] [http://www.myspace.com/kutebashrecords Kute Bash Records], which has released the London-based [[multimedia]] duo [[Tetine]]. In [[video art]], his interventions have been shown from [[nightclubs]] and [[Art museum|galleries]] in Europe to the public television in Brazil. In both his writing and videos, Ricardo Domeneck concentrates on his own body as fixed set of materials.\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n'''Poetry'''\n\n*  ''Carta aos anfibios'' (Rio de Janeiro: Editora Bem-Te-Vi, 2005) {{ISBN|85-88747-17-0}}\n*  ''a cadela sem Logos'' (S\u00e3o Paulo: Cosac Naify, 2007) {{ISBN|978-85-7503-568-9}}\n*  ''Sons: Arranjo: Garganta'' (S\u00e3o Paulo: Cosac Naify, 2009) {{ISBN|978-85-7503-778-2}}\n* ''Cigarros na cama'' (Rio de Janeiro: Berinjela/Modo de Usar & Co., 2011)\n\n'''Chapbooks'''\n\n* ''When they spoke I / confused cortex / for context'' (London: Kute Bash Books, 2006)\n* ''Corpos e palanques'' (S\u00e3o Paulo: Dulcineia Catadora, 2009)\n\n'''Anthologies in Translation'''\n\n* ''Cuatro Poetas Recientes del Brasil'' (Buenos Aires: Black & Vermelho, 2006) {{ISBN|987-22223-2-0}}\n* ''\u00dcberland und Leuchtende St\u00e4dte \u2013 12 Dichterinnen und Dichter aus Lateinamerika'' (Berlin: SuKulTur, 2006) {{ISBN|3-937737-74-X}}\n* ''Tigertail Poetry Annual: Brazil Issue'' (Miami: Tigertail, 2008).\n* ''Dnevi poezije in vina'' (Ljubljana: \u0160tudentska zalo\u017eba, 2009)\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.greeninteger.com/green_integer_review/issue_9/Ricardo-Domeneck.cfm Poems on ''Green Integer Review'' issue 9]\n* [http://www2.tvcultura.com.br/entrelinhas/videos.asp?videodata=20/12/2006 Videos on Brazilian television network TV Cultura]\n* [http://www.myspace.com/ricardodomeneck Videos and sound poems on Myspace]\n* [http://www.lateinamerikanachrichten.de/?/artikel/1007.html German article on ''Lateinamerikanachrichten'']\n* [http://p.php.uol.com.br/tropico/html/textos/2616,1.shl Portuguese article about the poet on ''Tr\u00f3pico'']\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Domeneck}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Bebedouro]]\n[[Category:21st-century Brazilian poets]]\n[[Category:Brazilian male poets]]\n[[Category:Video artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Brazilian male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ricardo_Domeneck"}
{"title_page": "Lex Heinze", "text_new": "{{Expand German|Lex Heinze|topic=history|date=April 2013}}\nThe '''Lex Heinze''' (Latin: ''Heinze Law'') was a controversial law of 1900 amending Germany's Reich Criminal Code, named after the Berlin pimp Heinze, who was accused and convicted of committing \"bodily injury resulting in death\". It censored the public display of the \"immoral\" in artworks, literature and theatre and made [[pimp]]ing a criminal offence. After numerous public protests and resistance by several circles within the liberal middle class and the [[Social Democratic Party of Germany|Social Democrats]], the [[Reichstag (German Empire)|Reichstag]] passed a looser version of the draft law and added a \"morality clause\" into the Reich Criminal Code as a compromise proposal.\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Das Buch von der Lex Heinze. Ein Kulturdokument aus dem Anfange des zwanzigsten Jahrhunderts. Hg. von [[Otto Falckenberg]]. L. Staackmann, Leipzig 1900.\n* [[Georg von Vollmar]]: F\u00fcr die Freiheit der Kunst! Rede gegen die \u00a7\u00a7 184 a und b der sogenannten Lex Heinze, gehalten in der Sitzung des Reichstages vom 15. M\u00e4rz 1900. L. Pickelmann, M\u00fcnchen 1900.\n* [[Hermann Roeren]]: Die Lex Heinze und ihre Gefahr f\u00fcr Kunst, Litteratur und Sittlichkeit. J. P. Bachem, K\u00f6ln 1910.\n* Peter Mast: K\u00fcnstlerische und wissenschaftliche Freiheit im Deutschen Reich 1890\u20131901. Umsturzvorlage und Lex Heinze sowie die F\u00e4lle Arons und Spahn im Schnittpunkt der Interessen von Besitzb\u00fcrgertum, Katholizismus und Staat. 3. Aufl. Sch\u00e4uble Verlag, Rheinfelden 1994. {{ISBN|3-87718-018-3}}\n\n[[Category:Legal history of Germany]]\n[[Category:1900 in Germany]]\n[[Category:1900 in law]]\n\n{{Germany-law-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Expand German|Lex Heinze|topic=history|date=April 2013}}\nThe '''Lex Heinze''' (Latin: ''Heinze Law'') was a controversial law of 1900 amending Germany's Reich Criminal Code, named after the Berlin pimp Heinze, who was accused and convicted of committing \"bodily injury resulting in death\". It censored the public display of the \"immoral\" in artworks, literature and theatre and made [[pimp]]ing a criminal offence. After numerous public protests and resistance by several circles within the liberal middle class and the [[Social Democratic Party of Germany|Social Democrats]], the [[Reichstag (German Empire)|Reichstag]] passed a looser version of the draft law and added a \"morality clause\" into the Reich Criminal Code as a compromise proposal.\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Das Buch von der Lex Heinze. Ein Kulturdokument aus dem Anfange des zwanzigsten Jahrhunderts. Hg. von [[Otto Falckenberg]]. L. Staackmann, Leipzig 1900.\n* [[Georg von Vollmar]]: F\u00fcr die Freiheit der Kunst! Rede gegen die \u00a7\u00a7 184 a und b der sogenannten Lex Heinze, gehalten in der Sitzung des Reichstages vom 15. M\u00e4rz 1900. L. Pickelmann, M\u00fcnchen 1900.\n* [[Hermann Roeren]]: Die Lex Heinze und ihre Gefahr f\u00fcr Kunst, Litteratur und Sittlichkeit. J. P. Bachem, K\u00f6ln 1910.\n* Peter Mast: K\u00fcnstlerische und wissenschaftliche Freiheit im Deutschen Reich 1890-1901. Umsturzvorlage und Lex Heinze sowie die F\u00e4lle Arons und Spahn im Schnittpunkt der Interessen von Besitzb\u00fcrgertum, Katholizismus und Staat. 3. Aufl. Sch\u00e4uble Verlag, Rheinfelden 1994. {{ISBN|3-87718-018-3}}\n\n[[Category:Legal history of Germany]]\n[[Category:1900 in Germany]]\n[[Category:1900 in law]]\n\n{{Germany-law-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBibliography:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1890-1901 \u2192 1890\u20131901", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lex_Heinze"}
{"title_page": "Noah Reid", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=February 2020}}\n{{Short description|Canadian actor and musician}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Noah Reid\n| image              = Noah_Reid_performing_at_The_Great_Hall_Toronto_Nov_20_2019.jpg\n| image_size         =\n| caption            = Reid performing at the Great Hall in Toronto in November 2019\n| birth_name         = Noah Nicholas Reid\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1987|05|29}}\n| birth_place        = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n| occupation         = Actor, musician\n| years_active       = 1996\u2013present\n}}\n'''Noah Nicholas Reid'''<ref>{{Citation|last=The Arts Guild|title=Interview with Noah Reid and Melanie Leishman about Old Stock|date=May 31, 2013|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0hp2xjy8-VQ|access-date=May 12, 2019}}</ref> (born May 29, 1987) is a Canadian actor and musician. He is known for his performances in several films and television series, including the critically acclaimed [[CBC Television|CBC]] comedy ''[[Schitt's Creek]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/01/schitts-creek-netflix-pop-success-story.html|title=The Unlikely Rise of Schitt's Creek|last=Adalian|first=Josef|date=January 16, 2019|website=www.vulture.com|access-date=March 22, 2019}}</ref> In 2016, he received a [[Canadian Screen Awards|Canadian Screen Award]] nomination for [[Academy of Canadian Cinema and Television Award for Best Achievement in Music \u2013 Original Song|Best Original Song]] for his work in the feature film ''[[People Hold On (film)|People Hold On]]''.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2019, he won a Canadian Screen Award for Best Supporting Actor in a Comedy for his work on ''Schitt's Creek''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BviKIzTBdrW/|title=Schitt's Creek on Instagram: \"WINNER! Congratulations Noah Reid, for your Best Supporting Actor in a Comedy Canadian Screen Award! #CdnScreenAwards\"|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=May 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nReid was born and raised in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2015/08/09/kevin-from-work-star-noah-reid-explores-the-art-of-awkwardness|title='Kevin From Work' star Noah Reid explores the art of awkwardness|website=Toronto Sun|access-date=January 21, 2017}}</ref> The son of visual artists, he became involved in theatre around age six and regularly attended productions with his family throughout his childhood.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.myentertainmentworld.ca/2018/03/noah-reid/|title=Nominee Interview Series: Noah Reid|last=Kelly \u00bb|date=March 18, 2018|website=My Entertainment World|language=en-US|access-date=May 25, 2019}}</ref> He attended [[Etobicoke School of the Arts]] and is a 2008 graduate<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ww2.ent-nts.ca/en/graduates-and-recent-cohorts/2008/|title=Graduates and recent cohorts|website=ww2.ent-nts.ca|language=en|access-date=May 17, 2019}}</ref> of the [[National Theatre School of Canada]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Career==\nAs a [[child actor]], Reid provided the [[Voice acting|voice]] of the title character in ''[[Franklin (TV series)|Franklin]]'', Tommy Settegren in 1997's ''[[Pippi Longstocking (1997 film)|Pippi Longstocking]]'', and has since co-starred in ''[[Strange Days at Blake Holsey High]]'', among other shows. Reid also provides the voice for Gunther in the animated series ''[[Jane and the Dragon (TV series)|Jane and the Dragon]]'' and Eddie in ''[[Marvin The Tap-Dancing Horse]]'', as well as various characters in ''[[Little Bear (TV series)|Little Bear]]'', ''[[Redwall (TV series)|Redwall]]'', ''[[Mythic Warriors: Guardians of the Legend]]'', ''[[Tales from the Cryptkeeper]]'', ''[[Timothy Goes to School]]'', ''[[The Berenstain Bears (2003 TV series)|The Berenstain Bears]]'', ''[[Babar: King of the Elephants]]'', and ''[[Bad Dog (TV series)|Bad Dog]]''.\n\nIn 2005, Reid played the role of Darrell Fox in the made-for-television movie ''Terry'' which dramatized [[Terry Fox]]'s [[Terry Fox Run|historic run for cancer research]]. In 2007, he appeared in the ''[[Naturally, Sadie]]'' episode \"[[List of Naturally, Sadie episodes|As the Whirly Turns]]\". In 2009, Reid guest-starred in the ''[[Degrassi: The Next Generation]]'' episode \"[[Degrassi: The Next Generation (season 8)|Danger Zone]]\".\n\nReid's first leading role in a feature film was Farley Gordon in ''[[Score: A Hockey Musical]]''\u2014which premiered at the [[2010 Toronto International Film Festival]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/posted-toronto/my-toronto-noah-reid-outdoor-rinks-hold-allure-for-score-star|title=My Toronto: Noah Reid \u2014 Outdoor rinks hold allure for Score star|newspaper=National Post|language=en|access-date=January 21, 2017}}</ref> Following this, he played several guest roles on television, including in the [[Police procedural|police drama]] ''[[Rookie Blue]]'' (2012) and the drama series ''[[Cracked (Canadian TV series)|Cracked]]'' (2013). In 2013, he also appeared in the [[The CW|CW]] [[web series]] ''[[Backpackers (web series)|Backpackers]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cwtvpr.com/the-cw/shows/backpackers/bios?id=noah-reid|title=The CW Press {{!}} Backpackers|website=www.cwtvpr.com|language=en|access-date=January 14, 2018}}</ref> In 2015, he played the lead role in the [[Freeform (TV channel)|ABC Family]] comedy series ''[[Kevin from Work|Kevin From Work]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/kevin-from-work-premiere-noah-reid-interview-1201568828/|title=ABC Family Taps Into 20-Something Mentality with Comedy 'Kevin From Work'|last=Wagmeister|first=Elizabeth|date=August 12, 2015|work=Variety|access-date=January 14, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> The series was canceled after one season.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://deadline.com/2016/03/kevin-from-work-canceled-freeform-one-season-1201714694/|title='Kevin From Work' Canceled By Freeform After One Season|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=March 4, 2016|work=Deadline|access-date=January 14, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Reid was nominated for a [[Canadian Screen Awards|Canadian Screen Award]] for [[Academy of Canadian Cinema and Television Award for Best Achievement in Music \u2013 Original Song|Best Original Song]] for his work in the feature film ''[[People Hold On (film)|People Hold On]]'' (2015), in which he also starred.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://globalnews.ca/news/2462969/2016-canadian-screen-awards-nominees-rookie-blue-vikings-big-brother-canada-nominated/|title=2016 Canadian Screen Awards nominees: 'Rookie Blue,' 'Vikings,' 'Big Brother Canada' nominated|last=Jancelewicz|first=Chris|website=Global News|access-date=April 7, 2016}}</ref> He also released a self-produced full length original album, ''Songs From a Broken Chair''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BIa1WKIBuhh/|title=Noah Reid on Instagram: \"Songs From A Broken Chair is now available on iTunes. Debut album. Playing a release show @burdockonbloor tonight, doors at 830. Thanks to\u2026\"|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=May 23, 2019}}</ref> \n\nIn 2017, Reid played the recurring role of Patrick in the [[List of Schitt's Creek episodes#Season 3 (2017)|third season]] of the [[CBC Television|CBC]] series ''[[Schitt's Creek]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.vulture.com/2017/11/pansexual-schitts-creek-character-wont-become-caricature.html|title=Dan Levy Won't Make Pansexual Schitt's Creek Character a 'Caricature'|last=Ferber|first=Taylor|work=Vulture|access-date=January 14, 2018|language=en}}</ref> That year, he was also cast in the independent film ''[[Cardinals (film)|Cardinals]]'', opposite [[Sheila McCarthy]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/kevin-work-star-noah-reid-879704|title='Kevin From Work' Star Noah Reid Nabs Lead in 'Cardinal' Drama (Exclusive)|work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=January 14, 2018|language=en}}</ref> which premiered at the [[2017 Toronto International Film Festival]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tiff.net/tiff/cardinals/|title=Cardinals|website=www.tiff.net|language=en|access-date=January 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Reid was promoted to a series regular on ''Schitt's Creek'', beginning with the series' [[List of Schitt's Creek episodes#Season 4 (2018)|fourth season]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tv-eh.com/2018/01/08/preview-schitts-creek/|title=Preview: The schitt hits the fan in Season 4 of CBC's Schitt's Creek|date=January 8, 2018|work=TV, eh?|access-date=January 14, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> He also performed in a production of ''[[Hamlet]]'' at the [[Tarragon Theatre]] in Toronto in the same year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/theatre-and-performance/theatre-reviews/review-something-is-off-in-tarragons-hamlet/article37579917/|title=Review: Something is off in Tarragon's reimagining of Hamlet|access-date=January 14, 2018}}</ref> In December, he recorded another original album, titled ''Gemini'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/video/6033309/schitts-creek-star-noah-reid-performs-jacobs-dream/|title=Schitt's Creek star Noah Reid performs 'Jacob's Dream' {{!}} Watch News Videos Online|website=Global News|language=en|access-date=December 5, 2019}}</ref> slated for a May 2020 release.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BwF6Sm8AF6q/|title=OutLoud Speakers School on Instagram: \"SPEAKER PROFILE! \u2013 NOAH REID Toronto born Noah Reid has been acting and writing music since he was 6 years old. At 9, he originated the\u2026\"|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=May 23, 2019}}</ref> He starred in the film ''[[Buffaloed]]'', which was released in February 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/02/13/804804244/buffaloed-debt-collecting-for-fun-and-profit|title='Buffaloed': Debt Collecting For Fun And Profit|website=[[NPR]]|date=February 13, 2020|last=Jenkins|first=Mark|access-date=February 29, 2020}}</ref> Reid will also tour to promote ''Gemini'', with dates in Canada and the US.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B4z1MQnhOdV/|title=Noah Reid on Instagram: \"\ud83d\udea8MORE CITIES \ud83d\udea8Very excited to announce that we've added Ann Arbor, Chicago and Washington to the First Time Out Tour and that my good\u2026\"|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=December 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nReid announced his engagement to actress [[Clare Stone]] on December 31, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BsEKXG8no5K/|title=Noah Reid on Instagram: Roommates for life \ud83d\udc8d|last=|first=|date=December 31, 2018|website=Instagram|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Reid is a dual Canadian-US citizen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ggagency.ca/reid/|title=Reid|date=July 8, 2015|website=Gary Goddard Agency|language=en-CA|access-date=May 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:85%;\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 1996 || ''[[In Love and War (1996 film)|In Love and War]]'' || Boy ||\n|-\n| 1997\u20131999 || ''[[Pippi Longstocking (1997 TV series)|Pippi Longstocking]]'' || Tommy Settergren (voice) || 22 episodes; credited as Noah Reed\n|-\n| 1997\u20131999 || ''The Treehouse Club'' || Himself ||\n|-\n| 1997\u20132004 || ''[[Franklin (TV series)|Franklin]]'' || Franklin (voice) || 31 episodes\n|-\n| 1998 || ''[[The Secret of NIMH 2: Timmy to the Rescue]]'' || Timmy Brisby's Singing Voice (Uncredited) ||\n|-\n| 2000\u20132001 || ''[[In a Heartbeat (TV series)|In a Heartbeat]]'' || Mark || 4 episodes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"| 2000 || ''[[Redwall (TV series)#Mattimeo|Mattimeo: A Tale of Redwall]]'' || Scurl Droptail (voice) ||\n|-\n| ''[[Franklin and the Green Knight]]'' || Franklin Turtle (voice) || [[Direct-to-video]]\n|-\n| ''[[Babar (TV series)|Babar]]'' || Pom (voice) || 13 episodes\n|-\n| ''[[Anne of Green Gables: The Animated Series]